title: For Sale:  m855a1
postcontent: This is not the common m855 “green tip” round. This is the enhanced performance round (ERP). The steel penetrator tip is a different tip from green tips. Also the load is hotter. The m855a1 also uses a stab crimp on the primer rather than the common circumferential crimp, which holds better under the higher pressures. I think Lake City is the only munitions plant that makes m855a1 rounds, but I might be wrong, either way, the rounds I am selling have the “LC” Lake City head stamp. Check out the videos on The Wound Channel on YouTube if you are not familiar with these rounds. Pricing is difficult on these rounds. On gunbroker.com the starting bid is $8/round. I see past prices here on armslist being from $7.50/round to $5.00/round. If I were on the buying end, I would be thinking that these are too high, especially the pricing upwards of $7. I guess I will ask for $4.00 a round, which is still pretty expensive in my mind. However, these are not easy to come by and others are asking for double what I am wanting to get out of these. I am also open to offers. Feel free to text at (509) Nine 9 Eight - 9 three 9 five or just email through the armslist service. I have a few other things I am selling as well in order to pay for some home improvements. I have a plate carrier with ceramic plates, a Mosin Nagant in monte carlo stock, and an AR-10 up for sale.UPDATE: Plate carrier with plates sold. I sold 25 rounds of the m855a1, have 75 left.

postcontent: If you can read this, it is still for sale.  I will Delete when sold.  F.I. (Firearms International) Industries, Model D .380 ACP. Made in the US 1973-1977 in Washington D.C. (of all places.) THIS IS NOT A COLT, but there's no option for FI and it was destined to be the Colt Pony. The internet says the CPA prefix for the serial numbers stood for "Colt Pony Auto" due to a pending deal for F.I. to make these to be sold as Colts.  Apparently the frame was to be made by Colt, the remainder of the parts supplied by Star and the pistol marketed by Colt as the "Pony".  That deal never happened (Colt was pretty chaotic during that time period) and FI made these for a few years.  Later Colt made the .380 Mustang. It's 6" total length, adjustable rear sight, and one original 6-round magazine. It's a single action semi-auto, like a little 1911 with the swinging link. It doesn't appear to have much wear on it.  Bore is excellent.  No Import Marks.  Nice well made, interesting pistol.

title: For Sale:  Ruger Vaquero Birdshead Case Hardened
postcontent: Up for sale is an ultra rare Ruger single action...more on the rare part in a minute.  This is a large frame (original Vaquero), not the current "New Vaquero" model.  The large frame originals are capable of "Ruger only" loads.  It's the blued model with Ruger's faux case hardened frame.  The revolver exhibits a slight turn line on the cylinder from handling but has not been fired outside of the Ruger factory.  The model number is 00511 and the catalog number is BNVBH-453.  Now the backstory on the rare part....Ruger transitioned from the original Vaquero to the new Vaquero late 2004 early 2005 timeframe and stopped making the originals.  Thus gun was made in April of 2010 (based on the spent shell casing that came with it from the factory), 5 years after the end of production and 5 years after Ruger stopped the faux case hardening on their blued single actions.  Furthermore, the notorious Ruger warning label on the barrel was much smaller and on the underside of the barrel.  Prior examples were larger and on the side of the barrel.  After acquiring, I called Ruger to verify the manufacter date.  Between that and the model/catalog number (which were unique to this particular gun), I was able to find out through a few searches this was one of Ruger's parts clean up releases that were only sold through Davidson's, and that there were likely less than 200 or so made.  The late production alone makes it a Ruger collector's object of desire, but the barrel warning label variation puts it over the top.   If interested, feel free to reply with your number.  I'd be happy to text additional pictures, including the factory label showing model/catalog as well as the dated spent casing.    Price is $650

title: For Sale:  1943 M1 Garand
postcontent:
Fantastic condition, miliary bundling still untouched in stock.  1943 January Receiver.
The M1 rifle is a .30 caliber, gas-operated, 8 shot clip-fed, semi-automatic rifle.[26] It is 43.6 inches (1,107 mm) long and it weighs about 9.5 pounds (4.31 kg).[27]The M1's safety catch is located at the front of the trigger guard. It is engaged when it is pressed rearward into the trigger guard, and disengaged when it is pushed forward and is protruding outside of the trigger guard.[28]The M1 Garand was designed for simple assembly and disassembly to facilitate field maintenance. It can be field stripped (broken down) without tools in just a few seconds.[29]The rifle had an iron sight line consisting of rear receiver aperture sight protected by sturdy "ears" calibrated for 100–1,200 yd (91–1,097 m) in 100 yd (91 m) increments. The bullet drop compensation was set by turning the range knob to the appropriate range setting. The bullet drop compensation/range knob can be fine adjusted by setting the rear sight elevation pinion. The elevation pinion can be fine adjusted in approximately 1 MOA increments. The aperture sight was also able to correct for wind drift operated by turning a windage knob that moved the sight in approximately 1 MOA increments. The windage lines on the receiver to indicate the windage setting were 4 MOA apart. The front sighting element consisted of a wing guards protected front post.During World War II the M1 rifle's semiautomatic operation gave United States infantrymen a significant advantage in firepower and shot-to-shot recovery time over enemy infantrymen armed primarily with bolt-action rifles. The semi-automatic operation and reduced recoil allowed soldiers to fire 8 rounds as quickly as they could pull the trigger, without having to move their hands on the rifle and therefore disrupt their firing position and point of aim.[30] The Garand's fire rate, in the hands of a trained soldier, averaged 40–50 accurate shots per minute at a range of 300 yards (270 m). "At ranges over 500 yards (460 m), a battlefield target is hard for the average rifleman to hit. Therefore, 500 yards (460 m) is considered the maximum effective range, even though the rifle is accurate at much greater ranges."
